bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Commonwealth Fund was established in 1918 with an endowment of $10 million from Mrs. Stephen V. Harkness for "benevolent, religious, educational and like purposes." The early grants supported a variety of programs while generally promoting welfare, especially child welfare. Several grants were made in the field of medical research, but the Board of Directors decided in 1920 that this field was already sufficiently supported by other philanthropic organizations.

Despite this decision, by the mid-1920s the chief interest of the Fund had become public health, including mental hygiene, community health, rural hospitals, medical research, and medical education. Other grant areas included war relief, educational and legal research, child welfare, and international medical fellowships.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Commonwealth Fund's Division of Publications series is concerned with the publishing of books, journals, articles, and pamphlets. This series consists of correspondence, reports, financial papers, and a few pamphlets and books. The documents are mostly concerned with the financing and publishing of books, and the relationship of the Division with the authors and publishing companies.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This subseries is divided into three sections: Books Received, No Books Received, and Miscellaneous. The sections Books Received and No Books Received are arranged alphabetically by author. The Miscellaneous section is arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The first two sections of this subseries consist of correspondence and financial papers. The Books Received section is concerned with receiving certain books from authors, while the No Books Received section is concerned with the opposite. The various manuscripts of "Patterns of Human Growth" by Edith Boyd are located in the Books Received section. The third section, Miscellaneous, consists of the papers of directors, consultants, and publishing companies. The subseries dates from the late 1960s to the early 1980s.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This subseries is concerned with the practical publishing of various Commonwealth Fund books. The subseries consists of correspondence and financial papers which deal with such publishing matters as bindings, engraving and jackets. The folders date from the 1940s to the 1960s. Most of the books are reviewed in the Review subseries.
